  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 유마(維摩) : '
    value: 유마힐(維摩詰) 거사(居士)는 석가여래의 제자였다.
english:
  title: Visiting a Monk at Dongsa Temple in Kim's High Yang Estate
  author: Seong Hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    At Dongsa Temple, I seek out a monk—
    steady in his seat upon the blue palanquin,
    stepping through the breath of emerald peaks.
    From mountain's north to mountain's south we journey.
    Trees obscure the stone at Golden Grain's ridge,
    the path winds through Blue Lotus Realm to its humble hermitage.

    The bell's voice, rocking the moon,
    starts awake the tired sleeper.
    Lamp-shadow, turned from the wind,
    illumines the sanctuary's depths.
    On the cushion where the old monk sits,
    the dust of worldly care has ceased.
    Each time I see him, I hear
    Vimalakirti's discourse through the night.

    In the front village, the grain is threshed—
    wild geese cry out their sorrow to the cool blue sky.
    Across the four directions, autumn gleams clear,
    the harvest hastens urgent and full.
    Mounds of golden grain heap the furrows high,
    polished pearls of rice tumble onto the threshing floor.
    Clear wind sweeps through ten thousand hamlets' joy,
    three harvests rich with plenty.

    No tax collector's urgent call is heard—
    each house raises fowl and millet in celebration's cup.

    In the back garden, chestnuts gather round the house,
    spaced among branches, green in the autumn deep.
    When the season ripens, the fruits hang thick.
    Wind splits the spiny husks, they fall in time.
    Frost paints the jade-white flesh, each one swells fat.
    Idly gathered from the orchard's edge,
    they offer gifts for ancestors' plates,
    then turned before the fire's warmth
    to ease the hollow of the morning's hunger.

    In this world, the monkey-keeper's craft knows no limit,
    yet joy and anger—their reasons escape us all.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Vimalakirti refers to the Buddhist sage Vimalakirti (維摩詰), a lay disciple of the Buddha known for his profound wisdom and his discourse on emptiness, frequently referenced in Buddhist literature as an ideal of spiritual understanding beyond monastic formality.
